WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:03.768 --> 00:00:05.903
Greetings followers.

00:00:06.837 --> 00:00:08.439
And settle in.

00:00:08.906 --> 00:00:12.576
Because I'm about to share
with you a true story

00:00:12.610 --> 00:00:16.914
about one of the most
zealous cults in the world.

00:00:17.448 --> 00:00:20.684
The story takes place
on the group's holiest day.

00:00:20.718 --> 00:00:22.453
Acolytes arrived at dawn,

00:00:22.486 --> 00:00:24.188
some having crossed oceans

00:00:24.188 --> 00:00:27.324
and sacrificed life savings
in order to get there.

00:00:27.658 --> 00:00:29.660
They came bearing
hand-beaded offerings

00:00:29.693 --> 00:00:35.466
inscribed with sacred numbers: 22, 13, 89.

00:00:35.499 --> 00:00:36.834
But this, my friends,

00:00:36.867 --> 00:00:40.671
is not the story of an apocalyptic sect
on a faraway compound.

00:00:40.704 --> 00:00:43.541
No, this was a Taylor Swift concert.

00:00:43.574 --> 00:00:45.543
(Laughter)

00:00:45.576 --> 00:00:46.710
I said it.

00:00:46.744 --> 00:00:48.612
The talismans are friendship bracelets,

00:00:48.612 --> 00:00:50.448
the biblical books are known as eras,

00:00:50.448 --> 00:00:53.184
and the charismatic leader
is a billionaire pop priestess

00:00:53.184 --> 00:00:55.820
who, let's be honest,
could probably rule the free world

00:00:55.853 --> 00:00:57.121
if she really wanted to.

00:00:58.155 --> 00:00:59.457
Now, don't get me wrong.

00:00:59.490 --> 00:01:01.559
I'm a deep-dyed "Red" album girlie.

00:01:01.592 --> 00:01:04.028
I'm not here to call out
Swifties as cult followers.

00:01:04.061 --> 00:01:05.296
No, I wouldn't dare.

00:01:07.498 --> 00:01:10.034
But I'm an author
and a cultural commentator

00:01:10.034 --> 00:01:12.069
with a background in linguistics.

00:01:12.103 --> 00:01:17.808
And I’m here to share how we’re all
susceptible to cult-ish thinking,

00:01:17.808 --> 00:01:19.343
for better and for worse.

00:01:19.376 --> 00:01:22.813
And our everyday vocabularies
are evidence of our devotion.

00:01:23.447 --> 00:01:26.283
I'm here to share
what to pay attention to,

00:01:26.283 --> 00:01:27.818
what to listen for,

00:01:27.852 --> 00:01:30.921
so that, as we move through these
inevitably culty times,

00:01:30.921 --> 00:01:34.058
we can stay both enchanted and empowered.

00:01:35.092 --> 00:01:37.528
Now, my fascination
with cults is personal.

00:01:37.561 --> 00:01:38.929
That's because of my dad.

00:01:39.330 --> 00:01:42.733
As a teenager, he was forced
to join Synanon,

00:01:42.766 --> 00:01:45.836
a '70s California compound
with matching overalls

00:01:45.870 --> 00:01:49.173
and a traumatizing truth-telling
ritual called The Game.

00:01:49.740 --> 00:01:51.208
But my dad escaped,

00:01:51.208 --> 00:01:52.943
became a neuroscientist,

00:01:52.977 --> 00:01:54.211
and brought up a nosy kid

00:01:54.211 --> 00:01:56.747
who became obsessed with understanding

00:01:56.780 --> 00:02:00.618
how to identify cultish influence
in everyday life.

00:02:01.685 --> 00:02:04.054
As I got older, I couldn't help but notice

00:02:04.054 --> 00:02:08.192
that the same language tactics
that my dad described in Synanon

00:02:08.225 --> 00:02:10.528
could be found kind of everywhere.

00:02:10.928 --> 00:02:13.464
Like, in my high school theater program

00:02:13.497 --> 00:02:15.766
and in the wellness industry

00:02:15.766 --> 00:02:17.501
and on my social media feed.

00:02:18.169 --> 00:02:20.971
That's how I came to study
the cultish spectrum,

00:02:20.971 --> 00:02:22.540
degrees of influence,

00:02:22.540 --> 00:02:25.075
none of which start out
with LSD and robes,

00:02:25.109 --> 00:02:28.512
but instead, sneakily, with words.

00:02:29.747 --> 00:02:32.082
I want to point out three
cultish language tactics

00:02:32.116 --> 00:02:33.617
to listen for in everyday life.

00:02:33.617 --> 00:02:36.320
The first is called
the thought-terminating cliche.

00:02:36.320 --> 00:02:39.890
Coined in 1961 by the psychiatrist
Robert Jay Lifton,

00:02:39.890 --> 00:02:42.626
thought-terminating cliches
are zingy stack expressions

00:02:42.660 --> 00:02:45.129
that are easy to memorize, easy to repeat

00:02:45.162 --> 00:02:48.232
and aimed at shutting down
independent thinking and questioning.

00:02:48.532 --> 00:02:50.467
So let's say you're a member of a group,

00:02:50.467 --> 00:02:53.137
and there's a rule
that you want to push back against.

00:02:53.170 --> 00:02:56.473
You might get hit with a phrase
like, "trust the process,"

00:02:56.473 --> 00:02:59.610
or "it's all in God's plan"
to shut you down.

00:03:00.311 --> 00:03:02.947
In Synanon, the phrase "act as if"

00:03:02.980 --> 00:03:06.483
effectively meant pretend
that you believe until you do.

00:03:06.951 --> 00:03:09.286
Today, in conspiracy theory-type groups,

00:03:09.320 --> 00:03:13.757
the phrase “do your research” basically
means “stop asking me about mine.”

00:03:13.791 --> 00:03:14.959
(Laughter)

00:03:14.992 --> 00:03:17.494
Next, I want to talk
about "us" versus "them" labels.

00:03:17.528 --> 00:03:21.098
In Synanon, defectors
were called "splitees."

00:03:21.098 --> 00:03:25.302
Today, you’ve got your “sheeple,”
your “NPCs,” your “industry plants.”

00:03:25.936 --> 00:03:31.041
When a label makes all of those people
seem unilaterally evil and us superior,

00:03:31.041 --> 00:03:32.309
that's a red flag.

00:03:32.710 --> 00:03:35.579
And thirdly, I want
to mention loaded language.

00:03:35.613 --> 00:03:37.648
Corporate synergistic visionaries.

00:03:37.648 --> 00:03:39.883
Wellness 5D consciousness.

00:03:39.917 --> 00:03:43.387
At first, emotionally charged buzzwords
like this feel like enlightenment.

00:03:43.854 --> 00:03:45.022
Then one day you wake up

00:03:45.055 --> 00:03:48.659
and you realize you've completely
surrendered your ability to talk and think

00:03:48.659 --> 00:03:49.927
for yourself.

00:03:50.961 --> 00:03:55.132
This language works because it plugs
straight into our cognitive biases.

00:03:55.165 --> 00:03:58.102
These deeply ingrained
decision-making shortcuts

00:03:58.135 --> 00:04:00.070
that developed in earlier human brains

00:04:00.070 --> 00:04:02.673
to help us process information
from the world around us

00:04:02.706 --> 00:04:03.941
enough to survive it.

00:04:03.974 --> 00:04:09.013
But today, mental magic tricks like
confirmation bias, the sunk cost fallacy,

00:04:09.046 --> 00:04:10.648
and the halo effect

00:04:10.681 --> 00:04:13.917
cause us to believe only the information
we already agree with,

00:04:13.917 --> 00:04:15.519
double down on sketchy choices

00:04:15.552 --> 00:04:18.289
and worship mortal human beings
we've never even met

00:04:18.322 --> 00:04:20.024
as all-knowing deities.

00:04:20.758 --> 00:04:24.028
This clash between our
once useful cognitive biases

00:04:24.061 --> 00:04:25.696
and the information age

00:04:25.696 --> 00:04:27.798
is this phenomenon that I've been calling

00:04:27.831 --> 00:04:29.466
magical overthinking.

00:04:30.067 --> 00:04:31.468
And it's a problem

00:04:31.468 --> 00:04:33.304
because studies show that social media

00:04:33.337 --> 00:04:36.106
has damaged our mental health
and our attention spans,

00:04:36.106 --> 00:04:39.510
all the while making
cultish leaders mega accessible.

00:04:39.943 --> 00:04:43.080
Who needs compounds
when you have comment sections?

00:04:44.581 --> 00:04:46.984
Now, I don't say this to freak anyone out.

00:04:47.951 --> 00:04:52.289
I'm just here to point out the difference
between awe and indoctrination.

00:04:52.323 --> 00:04:55.559
And I want to leave us
with a few tips to help us do that.

00:04:55.592 --> 00:04:56.727
First of all,

00:04:56.760 --> 00:04:59.330
when you find yourself
in a space, even a digital one,

00:04:59.330 --> 00:05:01.365
where you feel really
emotionally activated

00:05:01.365 --> 00:05:03.067
and you're using a lot of buzzwords

00:05:03.067 --> 00:05:05.269
that make you feel
like you're part of a tribe,

00:05:05.302 --> 00:05:06.637
but you can't really define

00:05:06.637 --> 00:05:09.106
exactly what you're saying
in plain English, or why,

00:05:09.139 --> 00:05:12.843
that's a sign to take a step back
and consult other sources.

00:05:12.876 --> 00:05:15.879
Next, pay attention to exit costs.

00:05:15.879 --> 00:05:18.382
Healthy groups might make
leaving feel awkward,

00:05:18.382 --> 00:05:21.185
but never apocalyptic or earth-shattering.

00:05:21.218 --> 00:05:24.321
And finally, we can use
cult language for good.

00:05:24.355 --> 00:05:26.256
Rousing chants, rhyming mantras,

00:05:26.290 --> 00:05:30.694
they can be used to make
true information catchy, too.

00:05:31.528 --> 00:05:34.231
I'm not here to take away
anyone's friendship bracelets.

00:05:34.732 --> 00:05:36.834
We need community more now than ever.

00:05:37.668 --> 00:05:42.673
So I think living
in this cultiest era of all time,

00:05:42.706 --> 00:05:45.542
the goal is not so much to be cult-proof,

00:05:45.576 --> 00:05:48.545
it's to be cult-literate.

00:05:49.380 --> 00:05:50.614
You follow?

00:05:50.647 --> 00:05:51.949
(Laughter)

00:05:51.949 --> 00:05:53.150
Thank you.

00:05:53.150 --> 00:05:54.318
(Applause)

